content: It is so great to see so many active members today.
First of all, let me congratulate tunnet99 for his achievement with last homework - double best!
I will add the cp for the homeworks tonight, after lesson.
Guest983, you don't need to say that. :P

aivo, xiebin123xie, Alan, luwenzhe, slamduk, tieuphilac, eastmen, coco_yuang, tunnet99, killer21st, Renjufans, mumax, smiling, span, wetcat, fallnavy, shuwang, nick_hopper, weigui, Intotherenju, whte, Ikon, littlewhite, Chancewu, penitent, shaoping, moocheng, yyfcsd, AWP, renjunewbie, yzhnie, jiujiumei, pengyu, 8914643, Silver, Morden, shuker.
Last week we studied the lesson of tactics,
Shortly speaking, to make 4x4 is less likely to happen in early stage of the game..
3x3 takes less black stones to be set,
therefore it is likely to happen in early stage,
we rarely make 3x3 after 50-60 moves, because the board is getting full,
and there are too many fake threes
so, when we consider the 3x3 as the main white weapon in early stages,
then 4x4 is a good weapon for ending phase of the game
To be sure what we are talking about, lets quickly review the 4x4.
4x4 is forbidden if there are at least two fours which can make winning five in the next move.
1,3,5 cannot make winning 5 because of overline
because one of the fours cannot make winning five,
cause it makes only one four from which we can make five
but absense of winning 5 is the reason
nearly same meaning, but still different
because, there can be many reasons why 4 cannot become winning five
and we cannot put all those reasons into one definition
but if we just refer to this as "cannot make winning five"
then it is more clear to us.
it seems there is no problem about detecting 4x4

Chancewu, Intotherenju, slamduk, fallnavy, tunnet99, pengyu, killer21st, span, shaoping, luwenzhe, penitent, whte, renjunewbie, nick_hopper, eastmen, Renjufans, yyfcsd, littlewhite, shuwang, aivo, jiujiumei, wetcat, Silver, Alan, yzhnie, moocheng, mumax, 8914643, AWP, concord2497, weigui, pseudonym, Ikon, smiling, Morden.
so, now that you know what 4x4 is, and what types of 4x4 exist, and how to detect them.
we can go on with the tactics part.
white can use the 4x4 as a powerful weapon.
while pushing 3x3 was sometimes just a method to get some useful points or temp,
We can begin with the example of 4x4 from last homework.
i lose it, missed a 44 foul
here, there are two potential 4x4 points
It is not hard to see such 4x4 here
so, these two 4x4 helped white win
but did you notice that in this case, the 4x4 appeared out of VCT,
which means, everything was quite forced,
and both white and black did not have to be creative, or do effort,
so, as long as you have forced 4x4, everything is simple.
Here, only small thing decides who is the winner...
this variant would become black win
see how white fored the black stones
i did the same match in 263 game
so, we can say, there are two kinds of 4x4:
one kind is what just happens to come on the way
being part of the VCT process
like this one and last one
and the second kind of 4x4 where we need to compose the black stones
It is not easy to compose 4x4.
Because, it takes at least 8 black stones,
to be in perfect place, in perfect time,
and have the suitable white line attacking the 4x4 point
to have all this - nearly impossible task in creative play
On the other hand, in real tournaments you play against real players.
there are no books, programs, vct finders etc
so being creative is so important~
so, when you play against real players, there is always a chance for creativity and chance for mistakes.
the player is too nervous, because the game is important,
or the time is running out on clock
but those reasons make people make mistakes.
we may think, to create 4 black stones, and our own attacking white line may be hard,
but the reality shows that in real tournaments all is possible.
since early years of my renju career,
i begab to experiment with long games,
and while other games ended with draw after 100 moves, many of my games ended with 4x4
i dont think i am good or too creative or smart..
the opponent usually does not believe there can be any danger amymore
especially when nearly the whole board is full..
also, he may have a time-trouble,
which does not allow him think precisely.
In the future, we will have the whole lesson about the tactics of clocks
and how to use yoru own time and opponents time
and how to make opponents time be on the edge just before you plan your 4x4 traps
it will be in the lesson of clocks...
it is very skilful tactics to control the clock and time
today we will focus on the 4x4 forks.
I will show several of my old games...
in all the examples, i will explain
This game, I played as white, nearly 10 years ago.
My opponent was a strong Russian player.
here both me and my opponent spent lots of time on thinking...
he was searching for his win chance..
but no win.. so he balanced.
By now, white is doing well.
However, what is good, doesnt always mean win,
white has to work hard in the name of victory.
you may think f3 is strong point
but actually white is more worried about g6 point
so, move after move, the game went on... and white win was out of sight..
ok , then i went to new corner
white win is still out of sight
I hoped I can win here.
but the inner structures are not standing so well
so white doesnt get much support from the inner material
and by the 67th move, my opponent started to hope for the draw.
other people around the table, watching the game, seemed confident in draw result too
there is almost no white material..
so here i used the first tactics of long 4x4 preparation:
i made move 66, to force him to think of dilemma..
to defend or not to defend..
actually, i did not study win for 66th move.
I assumed he would block there, it is natural human reflex
Did you have any plan other for consuming his time by 66th?
he did not have much time
i was planning the lower side attack actually,
in you want to put pressure on opponent,
then do not immediately begin with the "real" area
but put him into "thoughts" on another area
and while he was pondering over move 67..
i was calculating my possibilities in lower corner,,
i was worried he might notice that the move 66 was the time-killer,
for example, if he noticed that i am not looking at upper side at all
and just staring the lower area
so i even covered my eyesight with hands
so he could no see my eyes
at that time,he should watching your eyes
so, he spent lots of his time,..
allways keep your hands over your face)
but then i looked at his clock
he still had some minutes left.
it was too early for f3...
i hope i can be a fox too~
please note that the time-killer at 70th made black to use a four to k5..
actually we can agree it was not necessary for defense..
but he thought to play four is even better, stronger defense on right side
but he did not notice the minor details, happening on left wing..
by playing to k5, he blocked his pair at i7..
but will offer some benefit for me in further 4x4 planning..
because, if k5 was not played,
it means, black could spare that four,
and later use it for defense,
either k5 with timing, or to i7
tiny change will make big difference
but  i  don't  unstand much  english
so moves 68 and 72 were helpful in both killing time, and weakening black structures.
Now, of course, white will make as many moves as possible on right corner,
9 stones,do RT want  to catch 4*4 in here line?
the exact details of 4x4 will be seen later
There are certain structures required for 4x4
and I was building them little by little.
i maybe left  a little  time:)
here, white is preparing one pseudo-4x4
it looks as if white was going to force 4x4 soon to point b6..
as you see, white has a kind of way to force black stone to e9
and, it is quite likely, that both f3 point and c3 point would likely force black stone to f6 sooner or later,
so b6 will become more and more realistic trap
my opponent was concerned about this trap...
and decided to play here, giving him the kind of four, to help him to avoid trap
i still think f3 is early...
already so many moves ago, i imagined of true final 4x4..
but i knew he would never be trapped, if he had enough time to focus on defense..
so c3 move was another preparation move.
now he was afraid of overline..
actually, the real idea was to clear off the diagonal b6_c5_d4_e3.. which could annoy whites later.
and he had like 20 seconds of time left on clock
the magic of this situation is..
i dont know if you have played any serious tournament game having 20 seconds left..
but the mental condition is very weird..
one may even see the 4x4 coming
but doesnt know HOW TO AVOID?
he knows there are moves that can avoid the trap
but mind stops thinking of logical moves
in such moments, the insticts take control
I think his 87 may not good
this game is just an example of how to prepare the 4x4 in long term
we dont need to think what was good black move here
the game was s upposed to be draw,
but i explained that 4x4 is possible

Intotherenju, eastmen, tunnet99, whte, penitent, span, Renjufans, coco_yuang, Rauni, luwenzhe, mumax, pengyu, renjunewbie, pseudonym, Ikon, shuwang, Alan, fallnavy, shaoping, 8914643, slamduk, weigui, littlewhite, moocheng, yyfcsd, wetcat, Chancewu, yzhnie, shadewawa, xiebin123xie, aivo, Silver, smiling, Morden.
the black player of the last game was Victor Alexandrov
and the game was from european team championship 1994
this game that i am about to show was played even earlier,
some of you have seen it,
but i just explain the 4x4 here
i defended 3x3, as it is often best defense.
ok, this was the turning point of the game.
I had gotten the initiative here,
Black had secured most of the space on board
those white space moves are nice try, but actually powerless,
because inner structures do not support the white's space move
so he spent time to avoid trap here
And the win hope that white dreamed of, was gone.
that game, we both had time-trouble..
i had to close the three..
he did not see this win coming at all...
because of it, the trap was not working again
I had "one last shot" for that trap
he is top ranking player in the renju world
it was needed... i knew it
you may wonder why did i need 38_88_20..
the reason is, i had to play f12 sooner or later,
to make the a7 trap work again
and i needed to have "something" there in upper area
that would let my opponent focus there
so when i now played f12,
if i did not have that line,
he likmely would have seen the a7 coming..
but he did not see, because the 38_88_20 blinded him
he did not speak any english then
but he took the stone in his hand,
and spoke first time, after putting stone "draw?", he asked
and add stones for his oppenont
did you smiled to him RT?
another game, with Pogosyan, from same WC
now, from WC 97.. my game with Stefan Karlsson
so tired to play with you:(
at that time i did not know white win from opening
I hoped to win on left,,
so i began doing something on right
I was not sure b10 could win..
at least i didnt see any win when i counted it
but he had short in time
but he found the correct move
so that he could think motre over his 4x4 problem
I was forced to think some time about his threats
and he got extra time by that for his own thinking
I was now planning 4x4 to m8..
and then he made mistake with 95
and black will die one of 4x4s
you wonder, why i played 90 for preparing the trap
so, in order to prevent this counter-play,
I hoped he would follow my 90
and i hoped he would go L13
sometimes you know your opponents moves

and learned how to make them..
this would be a good puzzle :)
it was my first WC game ever..
i just joined first time WC, and first round
we were both newcomers, and nervous
the beauty of this 4x4x4x4 is that all the four here are natural,
none of the fours was added in purpose
they just appeard on the way
I hope, todays lesson gave you many ideas of how to trap 4x4. It is powerful knowledge.
